(4, 1, '2010-06-05 15:23:28', '2010-06-05 15:23:28', 'I am currently a researcher in the Laboratory of Neurogenetics at Duke University, working under Professor Ahmad Hariri.  We are studying how variability in neural circuitry can lead to individual differences in behavior, and how these differences in brain function can further be connected to an individual''s genes.  We use fMRI to study pathways implicated in anxiety, depression, and reward at the Brain Imaging and Analysis Center (BIAC) at Duke.\n\nNeuroimaging combined with behavioral, cognitive, and genetic assessments allow us to look for connections between these molecular signaling pathways and functional genetic polymorphisms that could possibly be the basis for the variability in neural circuitry, and subsequently, behavior.\n\nThe goal at the end of the day is to better understand the neurobiology of individual differences in complex behavioral traits, and to work towards the development of effective, personalized treatment.  I am excited that our research could ultimately lead to a better understanding of predictive risk markers of neuropsychiatric disease, and how the individual is shaped by the environment.&lt;/p&gt;\\r\\n&lt;p&gt;I am passionate about this research and immensely enjoy all aspects of it!  I welcome you to visit our lab\\''s website to learn more.', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2-autosave', '', '', '2010-06-05 15:23:28', '2010-06-05 15:23:28', '', 2, 'http://www.vsoch.com/?p=4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
